<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Chickpeas Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>Supply Chain Disruptions:</strong> The chickpeas market faced significant supply chain disruptions due to factors such as climate change, geopolitical tensions, and global pandemics. These disruptions impact the availability and cost of raw materials.</li>    <li><strong>Quality Control Issues:</strong> Inconsistent quality of chickpeas due to varying farming practices and soil health can affect buyer satisfaction and market stability. Maintaining high quality standards across regions remains a challenge.</li>    <li><strong>Price Volatility:</strong> The price of chickpeas can fluctuate significantly due to market demand, changing agricultural practices, and competing crops. This volatility poses risks for farmers and end consumers alike.</li>    <li><strong>Awareness and Education:</strong> Despite the nutritional benefits of chickpeas, there remains a lack of awareness among some consumer segments about their health benefits and versatility as a food source. This gap can limit market penetration.</li>    <li><strong>Competition from Alternative Proteins:</strong> The growing popularity of other plant-based proteins and alternatives can overshadow the chickpea market. This impact may stem from marketing strength, perceived health benefits, or culinary applications.</li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Chickpeas Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>Health Trends:</strong> With the rising trend toward healthy eating, chickpeas provide an excellent opportunity for market expansion. They are high in protein and fiber, catering to health-conscious consumers, including vegans and vegetarians.</li>    <li><strong>Innovative Food Products:</strong> There is growing innovation in food processing, leading to new products such as chickpea pasta, snacks, and flour. These products can attract a broader consumer base and adapt to evolving culinary trends.</li>    <li><strong>Export Potential: